                <componentInstanceProperties>
                    <name>richTextValue</name>
                    <value>&lt;h3&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anderson Content Standard Checklist V0.9.5&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Date:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Author:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Coach:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article #:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Targeted: Does this solve a real friction point? Did someone actually get stuck on this?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Does this article exist because someone actually got stuck?&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;We are not renewing information if we draft articles in anticipation of a question. If you can&apos;t connect it to a real situation that comes up at ABA, that’s a problem worth flagging.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Could even a coach determine this? &quot;If the situation isn&apos;t obvious from the article itself, ask the author to name it. If they can&apos;t, that&apos;s the flag.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Coaching Action:&lt;/strong&gt; If you can&apos;t connect it to a real situation that comes up at ABA, flag it and send it back. Don&apos;t approve articles written, &quot;just in case.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Scoped: One question, one answer? Or is this really three articles?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Does the draft describe one situation and ask one question?&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Coaching Action:&lt;/strong&gt; A reader needs to be able to find the situation, then question. If it&apos;s hard to parse or covers multiple scenarios, it&apos;s either two articles or a problem statement that needs tightening. Send it back with that note.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Linked: Are related articles connected?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;If this article touches a process connected to another KB article, link it. Don&apos;t repeat that content here.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Original: Does another article already answer this question?&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Coaching Action:&lt;/strong&gt; Search the KB for the title keywords before approving. If a match exists, the author should refine that article instead. Two articles answering the same question split search results.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Findable: Would someone searching find this? Does the title match what they&apos;d type?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Does it tell the reader whether this applies to them?&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Apply the same test to the problem description.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Is it written in the words the client or employee would use when confused?&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Critical:&lt;/strong&gt; failure here = return regardless of total score.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Coaching Action:&lt;/strong&gt; Read the title as a first-time user. Is this a way you would search for this information?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Trustworthy: Would someone act on this without checking with a coworker or pulling up a secondary source?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;This is the Trust Test.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;A staff member could act on this in a tax or compliance situation, and the outcome would be correct.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Critical:&lt;/strong&gt; failure here = return regardless of total score.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Clear: Could someone new follow this without help?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Steps should be one discrete action each.&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Check:&lt;/em&gt; open, verify, select, file, confirm. Not &quot;you will need to&quot; or &quot;it is important to.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;If a step has nested sub-decisions, it probably needs its own article.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Workarounds must be labeled as such.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Critical:&lt;/strong&gt; failure here = return regardless of total score.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;</value>
                </componentInstanceProperties>
